We know the last few months have been hard, and Worthington leaders want to know how best to help. We invite you to fill out this survey about what's happening in your life during the coronavirus outbreak.

The information you share will be used to help the City of Worthington and other organizations serving the greater Worthington area to understand the impact of the coronavirus outbreak on the people in our community.

Your responses, along with the responses of others in our community, will help us to identify areas of need and guide our future response to this ongoing crisis. Thank you!

#ItsWorthIt

post_text:
They say the show must go on and it did for Worthington Hills 6th graders this week.

The school buildings were shut down just before their Willy Wonka Jr. show last year. After working hard all summer with the kids & remotely recording their performances, music teacher Kara Johansen debuted all of the students' show as a movie!

As one parent wrote us, "As we watched the movie, our kids learned what it truly means to have an educator who cares deeply about them, who believes in them and who will go the extra mile."

#ItsWorthIt
text:
They say the show must go on and it did for Worthington Hills 6th graders this week.

The school buildings were shut down just before their Willy Wonka Jr. show last year. After working hard all summer with the kids & remotely recording their performances, music teacher Kara Johansen debuted all of the students' show as a movie!

As one parent wrote us, "As we watched the movie, our kids learned what it truly means to have an educator who cares deeply about them, who believes in them and who will go the extra mile."

#ItsWorthIt

The following information was just emailed out to parents & posted to Dr. Bowers' blog as we have received updates from local health departments.

"This week we sent remote learning schedules to all families. We’re ready to begin in that mode and that’s still the approved plan.

However, as a school district, we have said from the beginning that we desire to have our students in school. To meet Ohio’s Responsible Restart guidelines and socially distance that likely means a hybrid mode of schooling. If such a mode is deemed safe by public health, we feel like that’s our responsibility."

#ItsWorthIt

post_text:
"In Worthington Schools, I’d like to move from point A to point B easily. I’d like to be done with this COVID-19. I’d like to be able to answer everyone’s questions about what the future holds. I’d like to have an easy answer for how we will fix racial justice throughout the school district. But, right now the best we may be able to do is move 20 steps forward at a time."

Dr. Bowers talks about making slow & steady progress in these unprecedented times.

#ItsWorthIt

"Our seniors need to know the truth about themselves. They have everything they need inside them to be successful. They weren’t meant to be average. They have a desire to be great because they were created and born to go do great things. They have a purpose. There’s a plan for their life. They may be going through a hard time this Spring but they will get through this. It looks like the end of the world but it isn’t. This too shall pass." Read more from Superintendent Trent Bowers.

#ItsWorthIt

post_text:
Although we cannot meet in person for after school enrichment programming, Worthington is excited to share virtual enrichment opportunities - some try-it-out sessions in May and more extended sessions this summer.

One of the important lessons of remote learning has been that our students benefit from "seeing" peers and socializing in a meaningful way. 6Crickets, the platform we use for registration, has curated classes on a variety of topics, including engineering, robotics, life skills, math, yoga, dance, music production, French, and Spanish. All the providers are Ohio providers and many have served Worthington in the past -- they have worked hard to create online classes.

Go to https://www.worthington.k12.oh.us/6crickets for more info and to register.

#ItsWorthIt

"We’d like to gather and do all of our normal things. We’d like to have graduation, prom, 6th grade camp, clap-outs and end of year recognitions and parties. That’s what we do and someday we will do them all again. In the meantime we need to find ways to take what we used to do and do it differently and make it as meaningful and maybe more meaningful than what we normally do."

#ItsWorthIt
shared_text:

Different but Meaningful
text:
"We’d like to gather and do all of our normal things. We’d like to have graduation, prom, 6th grade camp, clap-outs and end of year recognitions and parties. That’s what we do and someday we will do them all again. In the meantime we need to find ways to take what we used to do and do it differently and make it as meaningful and maybe more meaningful than what we normally do."

Read more in Dr. Bowers latest blog post:

#ItsWorthIt

WCSDISTRICT.WORDPRESS.COM
Different but Meaningful

REMINDER: Food service distribution of meals is on Mondays and Wednesdays now!

On Mondays, two days worth of meals will be given to families. On Wednesdays, three days worth of meals will be distributed.

Families can pick up the food during the same times/locations as they currently do: 10 a.m. - 1 p.m. at Thomas Worthington High School, Worthington Kilbourne High School and Slate Hill Elementary every Monday and Wednesday.

In addition to pick up locations, two buses will be distributing meals in Worthington neighborhoods on Mondays and Wednesdays. Please refer to the list of stops below.

Stops on Route 1
10:05 a.m. - 8496 Seabright Dr at Ibson
10:12 a.m. - Smoky View Blvd. at Orinda Rd.
10:23 a.m. - 7646 Sancroft Road
10:30 a.m. - Aquaford Place at Hightower Dr.
10:39 a.m. - Bridewater Blvd at Fall Creek Lane

Stops on Route 2
10:12 a.m. - Wilson Hill Elementary
10:25 a.m. - Barnes Dr East Playground
10:39 a.m. - 1008 Annagladys Dr.
10:48 a.m. - Shelter House on Park Club Drive
10:58 a.m. - Storrow Dr at Startford Chase Drive
11:04 a.m. - 8072 Storrow Dr.

***UPDATED WITH ADDITIONAL STOP ON ROUTE 2***

IMPORTANT FOOD DISTRIBUTION ANNOUNCEMENT

In order to reach more families and help limit community spread of COVID-19, we are updating the way free breakfast/lunches are being distributed for Worthington families.

Starting on Monday, April 6th, Worthington will move to a TWO-DAY A WEEK distribution. On Mondays, two days worth of meals will be given to families. On Wednesdays, three days worth of meals will be distributed.

Families can pick up the food during the same times/locations as they currently do: 10 a.m. - 1 p.m. at Thomas Worthington High School, Worthington Kilbourne High School and Slate Hill Elementary every Monday and Wednesday.

In…

post_text:
An update from the Superintendent shared in ThisWeek Worthington:

A lot of us are feeling anxious about this time of uncertainty, and many of our children are feeling this way, too. Making sure our students have access to our school counselors, healthful meals and a time for physical activity are an important part of their daily schedule, too. Our staff members are reaching out to our students regularly to help address students’ emotional needs.

We also believe it is important that we continue to celebrate our successes and progress. Our students need to see that good things continue despite these challenges.

Read more at the link below. #ItsWorthIt

"I know these times are tough. They are tough in many ways. We see that. We have families with loved ones on the front lines taking care of those who are sick. We have families with lost income. Changes are happening so quickly and with such a big impact. While we cannot take that hardship away, we can support each other throughout all of this. Know that we are here to support you and your child."

Read the latest on what our Superintendent is seeing across the district and updates from the Governor.

post_text:
Welcome back, Mike!

Mike Weirick, 20, of Worthington, a junior at the University of Tampa, was one of 550 American college students on a ship that was supposed to enjoy a Semester at Sea. But the worldwide outbreak of the coronavirus prevented them from docking in countries like China and India and left them cruising in the Indian Ocean for weeks.

#ItsWorthIt #WorthingtonStrong #ForWorthington

post_text:
From Dr. Trent Bowers: During this closure, we’ll be working to support our students and families as best as we can. As we’re all learning and growing together there will be a great deal of trial and error. We’ll all need kind, constructive feedback if we’re going to improve. As a school district, we want to help every child learn as much as we possibly can even though schools are closed. We’ve asked our teachers simply to do the best they can. I’m confident that they will.

Read the entire blog at the link. #ItsWorthIt #ReduceTheCurve

post_text:
"I’ve talked with ten different Worthington kids over the past three days and all of them said the same thing, “I wish we were back in school.” Many of them admitted that a week or two ago they thought they wanted to be off school but now that they actually can’t be back it stinks. They miss their friends, their sports, their teachers. They miss small things like sitting in the library and talking at their table while they try to sneak food when Mrs. Poleway isn’t looking. They miss big things like their baseball games and their winter percussion. They miss being in school."

Read more in Dr. Bowers' latest blog post. #ItsWorthIt

You don’t know what you got till it’s gone

Thomas Worthington High School
300 West Granville Road
Worthington, OH 43085

Worthington Kilbourne High School
1499 Hard Road
Columbus, OH 43235

Slate Hill Elementary
7625 Alta View Blvd.
Columbus, OH 43085

We appreciate offers from community residents to help support the free meals program over this extended time away from school. There is a need for volunteers to help!

You can learn more by emailing volunteers@worthingtonresourcepantry.org.

post_text:
IMPORTANT INFORMATION on the planned extended closure for the Worthington School District!!!

In Worthington Schools, we will hold a STAFF ONLY day on Monday for professional learning. Students will begin their three-week extended closure at the end of the day on Friday, March 13. Beginning Friday, March 13, 2020, all athletic and extracurricular activities, including practices, are canceled until Friday, April 3, 2020, when we will reevaluate.

The Worthington School District is currently scheduled for Spring Break April 6 - 10. Because we will be off for the three weeks before that, we will instead plan to be back in school April 6. We recognize some families may have trips planned over break that cannot be changed. If that’s the case, we will work with you to excuse your students for your travel plans. More info will be forthcoming.

READ MORE AT THE LINK:

#ForWorthington

post_text:
Worthington Pancake Day Postponed:

Every day Worthington Schools’ officials are evaluating and re-evaluating decisions that need to be made to keep our families and staff members safe. Yesterday, Governor DeWine, along with Ohio Department of Health Director Amy Acton, M.D. MPH, made a recommendation that large, indoor gatherings in Ohio be canceled or postponed due to concerns over the spread of the coronavirus.

This decision is not an easy one, but we do think it is the right one. We have decided to postpone Pancake Day, scheduled for Saturday, March 14 at Worthington Kilbourne High School. Additional communication will be sent when we have more details.

We have posted other information regarding the novel coronavirus (COVID-19) on the district website.

post_text:
The Finley’s Smile 5k and Smile Mile is great for families and those looking to set their next PR! The event takes place at Liberty Park in Powell, on a soft gravel path and consists of a 5k and 1 mile(ish) walk/run. Finley Grace Hollinger was born with Leigh’s Disease, a mitochondrial disorder. In her short life with us, she taught us three important lessons which we summarize as “Love, Play, & Smile.”

The Finley’s Smile 5k and Smile Mile is the primary fundraiser for the nonprofit organization, Finley’s Smile. The goal of Finley’s Smile is to provide authentic experiences to children that build background knowledge and encourage families and loved ones to spend time together.

#ItsWorthIt

shared_text:
Ohio Department of Education
March 2 at 1:43 AM ·

✨ The 𝗪⭕️𝗡𝗗𝗘𝗥𝗦 of ⭕️𝗛𝗜𝗢! ✨ We’re celebrating #StatehoodDay and Ohio’s 217th birthday!

Catherine Hohman’s kindergarten students learned about many of Ohio’s wonders last week in their Worthington Schools learning community. It’s never too early (or too late) to learn about the people, places and things which have shaped our state and its history! #OhioEd
